hands_on_practices.solution:
1. For a zero-energy s-wave bound state in a spherical square well of depth $U$ and range $R$, the condition is
$$
U\,R^2 \;=\;\frac{\pi^2\hbar^2}{8\mu}\,.
$$
2. For the deuteron (p–n) system, $U=V_0$ and $\mu=\mu_{pn}=\frac{m_p m_n}{m_p+m_n}$, so
$$
V_0\,R^2 \;=\;\frac{\pi^2\hbar^2}{8\,\mu_{pn}}\,. 
\tag{1}
$$
3. For the di-neutron (n–n) system with the CIB shift $\Delta V$, the well depth is $U=V_0-\Delta V$ and $\mu=\mu_{nn}=m_n/2$. The zero-energy condition becomes
$$
\bigl(V_0-\Delta V_{\rm crit}\bigr)\,R^2 \;=\;\frac{\pi^2\hbar^2}{8\,\mu_{nn}}\,.
\tag{2}
$$
4. Divide (2) by (1):
$$
\frac{V_0-\Delta V_{\rm crit}}{V_0}
\;=\;
\frac{\displaystyle\frac{\pi^2\hbar^2}{8\,\mu_{nn}\,R^2}}
{\displaystyle\frac{\pi^2\hbar^2}{8\,\mu_{pn}\,R^2}}
\;=\;\frac{\mu_{pn}}{\mu_{nn}}\,.
$$
Hence
$$
V_0-\Delta V_{\rm crit}
\;=\;
V_0\,\frac{\mu_{pn}}{\mu_{nn}}
\;\Longrightarrow\;
\Delta V_{\rm crit}
\;=\;
V_0\Bigl(1-\frac{\mu_{pn}}{\mu_{nn}}\Bigr)\,.
$$
5. Substitute $\mu_{pn}=\frac{m_p m_n}{m_p+m_n}$ and $\mu_{nn}=\frac{m_n}{2}$:
$$
\frac{\mu_{pn}}{\mu_{nn}}
=
\frac{\displaystyle\frac{m_p m_n}{m_p+m_n}}
{\displaystyle\frac{m_n}{2}}
=
\frac{2m_p}{m_p+m_n}
\,,
$$
so
$$
\Delta V_{\rm crit}
=V_0\Bigl(1-\frac{2m_p}{m_p+m_n}\Bigr)
=V_0\frac{m_n-m_p}{m_p+m_n}\,.
$$

We denote the energy denominator by $\Delta E = E_i - E_\phi$.  The mixing amplitudes are

1. With both Coulomb and CSB interactions,
$$
\alpha = \frac{\langle\phi|V_{INC}|\Psi_i\rangle}{\Delta E}
= \frac{v_C + v_{CSB}}{\Delta E}
= \frac{v_C + \xi\,v_C}{\Delta E}
= \frac{v_C(1+\xi)}{\Delta E}\,. 
$$

2. With Coulomb only,
$$
\alpha_0 = \frac{\langle\phi|V_C|\Psi_i\rangle}{\Delta E}
= \frac{v_C}{\Delta E}\,. 
$$

The E1 transition rate $\Gamma\propto |\langle\Psi_f|M(E1)|\tilde\Psi_i\rangle|^2$ is, to first order in $\alpha$, proportional to $|\alpha|^2$.  Hence the ratio of rates is

$$
\mathcal{R}
= \frac{|\alpha|^2}{|\alpha_0|^2}
= \frac{\bigl|\frac{v_C(1+\xi)}{\Delta E}\bigr|^2}
       {\bigl|\frac{v_C}{\Delta E}\bigr|^2}
= |1+\xi|^2
= (1+\xi)^2\,,
$$
since $\xi$ is real.
